[2] New Zealand (South Island)
Date: Sun 23 Aug 2015
Source: Stuff [edited]
http://www.stuff.co.nz/national/health/71370118/whooping-cough-outbreak-continues-to-spread-through-south


The whooping cough outbreak in the south is continuing to spread. Over 200 people have reported having whooping cough in the last month, and the number is expected to rise. The outbreak is spreading across the South Island, after being centered in Central Otago. An increasing number of cases are being detected in Southland and further afield in Otago, including Dunedin.

Historically, a whooping cough outbreak happens once every 4 years -- with the last taking place in 2011/12. While the number of daily reports of patients believed to have whooping cough is declining, health officials expect the numbers to rise again in weeks to come.

Naomi Gough, the public health physician for the Southern District Health Board, said the total number of notifications of whooping cough has been 200 over 4 weeks. Over the last week there had been less than 5 notifications per day of people having whooping cough. At the peak of the outbreak, it was about 15 people per day. A notification included suspected cases, and only about 1/3 of notifications have been confirmed as whooping cough. She said the difference between suspected and confirmed cases highlighted the fact it was a "difficult disease to diagnose and doctors are being vigilant for possible cases".

In about half of the cases, the patient had not been immunized against whooping cough, or their vaccinations were not up-to-date.

[Byline: Ashleigh Stewart]

